        <section id="summary" class="section">
            <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
            <div class="executive-summary">
                <p>The United States faces a critical challenge in artificial intelligence governance. In 2024, state lawmakers introduced nearly <strong>700 AI-related bills</strong> across 45 states, with 113 enacted into law—a dramatic increase from just 191 bills in 2023. This explosive growth in state-level AI regulation has created a fragmented compliance landscape that threatens American innovation and disproportionately harms small businesses.</p>
                
                <p><strong>65% of small businesses</strong> are concerned about rising litigation and compliance costs from conflicting AI laws. California's regulations alone will impose nearly <strong>$16,000 in annual compliance costs</strong> on small businesses.</p>
                
                <p><strong>This policy brief recommends establishing a federal AI regulatory framework that preempts conflicting state regulations while preserving state authority to enforce consumer protection and anti-discrimination laws.</strong></p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="background" class="section">
            <h2>Background and Problem Statement</h2>
            
            <p>The absence of comprehensive federal AI legislation has created a vacuum that states have rushed to fill. In 2024, 46 states passed 238 new pieces of technology regulation, representing a <strong>163% increase</strong> from the previous year. This regulatory explosion covers diverse AI applications including automated decision-making in employment and credit, algorithmic bias prevention, deepfakes, and data privacy requirements.</p>

            <p>Colorado became the first state to pass comprehensive AI legislation with SB-205, effective June 2026. Other states including California, Connecticut, and Virginia have introduced their own distinct approaches, creating a patchwork of conflicting requirements.</p>

            <h3>Key Stakeholders</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Government Agencies:</strong> State and federal regulators with overlapping jurisdictions</li>
                <li><strong>Technology Companies:</strong> From major platforms to AI startups facing compliance challenges</li>
                <li><strong>Small Businesses:</strong> Using AI to scale operations but facing disproportionate costs</li>
                <li><strong>Consumers & Civil Society:</strong> Seeking protection from AI-related harms</li>
                <li><strong>Investors:</strong> Assessing regulatory uncertainty in AI markets</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>The Urgency</h3>
            <p>Research shows that Colorado's AI law alone could cost the state <strong>40,000 jobs and $7 billion</strong> in economic output by 2030. When faced with regulations like those in Colorado and California, one-third of small business owners stated they would scale down AI use, and another fifth would avoid AI altogether.</p>

            <p>A startup facing a 200% increase in compliance costs could see its operating margin shift from profitable at 13% to a loss of -7%. Without standardized frameworks, companies cannot accurately budget for compliance, creating legal uncertainty that advantages large corporations while stifling startup innovation.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="analysis" class="section">
