        <section id="options" class="section">
            <h2>Policy Options and Recommendation</h2>

            <div class="policy-option">
                <h3>Option 1: Maintain Status Quo (State-Led Regulation)</h3>
                <p>Allow states to continue developing their own AI frameworks without federal intervention.</p>
                <div class="pros-cons">
                    <div class="pros">
                        <h4>✓ Advantages</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Local tailoring to state needs</li>
                            <li>Policy experimentation</li>
                            <li>Faster response to issues</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="cons">
                        <h4>✗ Disadvantages</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Compliance chaos</li>
                            <li>Harms small businesses</li>
                            <li>Reduces competitiveness</li>
                            <li>Inconsistent protections</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="policy-option">
                <h3>Option 2: Comprehensive Federal Preemption</h3>
                <p>Enact a single federal AI law that preempts all state regulations and establishes uniform national standards.</p>
                <div class="pros-cons">
                    <div class="pros">
                        <h4>✓ Advantages</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Eliminates complexity</li>
                            <li>Consistent protections</li>
                            <li>Clear framework</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="cons">
                        <h4>✗ Disadvantages</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Politically difficult</li>
                            <li>May be too rigid</li>
                            <li>Overrides state innovations</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="policy-option recommended">
                <h3>Option 3: Federal Framework with State Enforcement Authority</h3>
                <p>Establish a federal AI regulatory framework focused on high-risk AI applications while preserving state authority to enforce existing consumer protection and anti-discrimination laws.</p>
                
                <div class="pros-cons">
                    <div class="pros">
                        <h4>✓ Why This Is Best</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Reduces Compliance Burden:</strong> One set of AI-specific requirements</li>
                            <li><strong>Preserves Federalism:</strong> States retain enforcement authority</li>
                            <li><strong>Encourages Innovation:</strong> Clear standards reduce uncertainty</li>
                            <li><strong>Protects Consumers:</strong> Baseline protections nationwide</li>
                            <li><strong>Politically Feasible:</strong> Balances state and federal interests</li>
                            <li><strong>Levels Playing Field:</strong> Small businesses can compete</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="cons">
                        <h4>Implementation Requirements</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Risk-based approach for high-risk AI</li>
                            <li>Mandatory transparency requirements</li>
                            <li>Impact assessment protocols</li>
                            <li>Consumer opt-out mechanisms</li>
                            <li>Safe harbor provisions</li>
                            <li>Technical assistance for small businesses</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <p style="margin-top: 20px;"><strong>This approach follows successful federal frameworks in areas like securities regulation, where federal standards establish a floor but states can enforce through their own consumer protection authorities. The economic evidence is compelling: reducing conflicting AI laws will enable American businesses to innovate without fear of inadvertent non-compliance while maintaining strong consumer protections.</strong></p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="section">
            <h2>Conclusion</h2>
            <p>The explosion of state AI regulation reflects genuine concerns about algorithmic discrimination and privacy. However, the current fragmented approach threatens American leadership in AI while failing to deliver consistent consumer protections.</p>
            
            <p>A federal framework that establishes clear standards while preserving state enforcement authority offers the best path forward. <strong>The cost of inaction is measured in billions of dollars of economic impact, lost opportunities, and diminished American competitiveness.</strong></p>
            
            <p><strong>Congress should act decisively in 2025 to establish this framework before the patchwork becomes irreversibly complex.</strong></p>
        </section>

        <section id="references" class="section references">
